Critical Vulnerabilities Identified
FINDING 1: Slowloris Denial of Service Vulnerability
Severity: HIGH
CVSS Score: 7.5 (High)
CVE: CVE-2007-6750
Affected Services: Ports 80, 8082, 8083
Description: Multiple web services were found vulnerable to Slowloris denial of service
attacks. This low-bandwidth attack enables an attacker to exhaust server connection pools
by opening multiple connections and sending partial HTTP requests, preventing legitimate
users from accessing services.
Technical Details:
# Nmap vulnerability detection output
PORT   STATE SERVICE
80/tcp open  http
| http-slowloris-check:
|   VULNERABLE:
|   Slowloris DOS attack
|     State: LIKELY VULNERABLE
|     IDs:  CVE:CVE-2007-6750
Business Impact:
Complete service outage potential
Revenue loss during attack
Customer trust damage
Regulatory compliance concerns (PCI DSS)
Proof of Concept:
Validated using Nmap NSE scripts
Confirmed susceptibility on 3 separate services
No actual attack executed (testing only)
Remediation:
1. Implement connection rate limiting
2. Configure request timeout values (10-20 seconds)
3. Set maximum concurrent connections per IP
4. Deploy DDoS mitigation service (Cloudflare, AWS Shield)
5. Implement HTTP/2 protocol (inherently resistant)
Remediation Status:  Fully remediated in follow-up assessment
FINDING 2: Publicly Accessible Administrative Login Panel
Severity: HIGH
CVSS Score: 7.3 (High)
CWE: CWE-425 (Direct Request / Forced Browsing)
Description: An administrative login panel for the mailing system was discovered publicly
accessible without IP-based access restrictions, rate limiting, or multi-factor authentication
requirements.
Technical Details:
URL: https://webmailer.[redacted]/admin/login
Authentication: Username/password only
Rate Limiting: None observed
CAPTCHA: Not present
MFA: Not implemented
Account Lockout: Not observed
Security Issues:
1. No geographic restrictions
2. Error messages reveal authentication failure details
3. “Forgot password” functionality present
4. No visible brute-force protection
5. Accessible to entire internet
Attack Vectors:
Credential brute-forcing
Credential stuffing (leaked password databases)
Password spraying
Username enumeration
Social engineering targeting admins
Business Impact:
Potential administrative access compromise
Email system takeover risk
Customer data exposure
Communication interception capability
Remediation:
1. Implement IP whitelisting (corporate IPs only)
2. Deploy multi-factor authentication (MFA)
3. Add CAPTCHA after 3 failed attempts
4. Implement account lockout policy
5. Add rate limiting (3-5 attempts per hour per IP)
6. Require VPN access for administrative functions
Remediation Status:  Fully remediated - IP restrictions implemented
